"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576736","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-12","<p>My Department has had extensive discussions over the last few months with commissioners, providers and representatives of supported housing tenants.</p><p>The Government will make an announcement in the autumn setting out its plans for the future funding arrangements for the supported housing sector.</p><p>It will also set out our plans for working with the sector and other key stakeholders to ensure the safe transition to the new model.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2016-09-12T15:59:23.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576736/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576736/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576736/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-06","Supported Housing: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent discussions he has had with supported housing providers on future funding for that sector; and when the Government plans to announce the outcome of its review on the funding of that sector.","false","Biography information for Peter Aldous","Waveney","Peter Aldous","45226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576737","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Government will continue to work closely with local areas and remains open to discussion on any devolution proposals that include strong, accountable governance and clear accountability, including the adoption of elected mayors.</p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy",,"2016-09-12T17:00:30.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576737/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576737/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576737/answer","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576737/answer/previousversion/11072","Biography information for Andrew Percy","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-06","Mayors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the Government's policy is on requiring local authorities to adopt elected mayors as part of further proposals for the devolution of powers to local areas.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","45214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576738","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-14","<p>Through the Spending Review the Government has committed to investing £8 billion to deliver 400,000 affordable housing starts, doubling our investment from 2018/19. This includes £1.6 billion towards delivering 100,000 affordable homes for rent by 2021.</p><p>Since April 2010, we have delivered over 293,000 affordable homes. Between 1997 and 2010 the stock of rented affordable homes fell by 420,000. Between 2010 and 2015, the stock of rented affordable homes rented increased by 64,000.</p><p>Alongside increasing supply, the Localism act 2011 has maintained the statutory 'reasonable preference' criteria which ensure that overall priority for social housing is given to those who need it most.</p><p>The introduction of fixed term tenancies in the Housing and Planning Act 2016 will ensure councils get the best use out of their social housing stock by focusing it on those who need it the most for as long as they need it.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2016-09-14T16:44:17.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576738/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576738/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576738/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-06","Social Rented Housing: Liverpool Wavertree","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to ensure access to social housing for people in Liverpool, Wavertree constituency who require such housing.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","45297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576739","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Secretary of State has confirmed that the Government expects to make an announcement on the way forward for supported housing in early autumn.</p><p>Full impact and equality impact assessments will be undertaken in due course.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-09-12T16:59:25.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576739/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576739/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576739/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-06","Supported Housing: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many supported housing providers in (a) Birmingham, Erdington constituency and (b) the West Midlands will be affected by the local housing allowance cap on supported housing.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","45261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576740","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-12","<p>The department does not centrally hold information on the numbers on tenants in supported housing. The Homes and Communities Agency does publish information on the total stock of supported housing units in its statistical data return which is publically available online: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistical-data-return-statistical-releases" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistical-data-return-statistical-releases</a></p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2016-09-12T15:59:47.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576740/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576740/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576740/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-06","Supported Housing: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many tenants in (a) Birmingham, Erdington constituency and (b) the West Midlands live in supported housing owned by social landlords.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","45263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576741","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-14","<p>The Troubled Families Programme has an important role to play in tackling disadvantage and poverty through its focus on families affected by complex, multiple problems in England. The programme encourages services to consider the overlapping nature of problems which families face - tackling the root causes rather than responding to each problem in isolation. It promotes a new way of working, with services coming together - typically through one dedicated worker - working with and understanding the needs of the whole family instead of constantly reacting to their individual problems.</p><p>Through the original programme, launched in 2012, over 116,000 families had their lives 'turned around' using the criteria of the first programme, with children back in school; youth crime and anti-social behaviour significantly reduced; and over 18,000 adults from troubled families into work. The new expanded programme now aims to support 400,000 families with multiple, complex problems by 2020, and transform for the long term the way that public services work with families facing multiple disadvantages.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-09-14T16:38:27.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576741/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576741/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576741/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-06","Families: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effect that the Government's Troubled Families programme has had on meeting its objectives related to underprivileged communities.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","45100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576742","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-14","<p>My department continues to fund the work of the Planning Advisory Service, which exists to help local planning authorities share best practice, improve procedures and understand changes in national legislation and policy. Its current work concentrates in particular on places that need to prepare up-to-date plans and improve their development management services.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2016-09-14T16:39:29.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576742/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576742/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-06","Planning","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to ensure that best practice in planning is shared between local authorities.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","45076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576743","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-14","<p>Sir Eric Ollerenshaw's independent review recognised the successful implementation of local council tax support schemes by local government and made a number of recommendations which the government is now considering.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-09-14T16:38:53.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576743/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576743/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-06","Local Council Tax Support Schemes Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which of the recommendations made by the Ollerenshaw Review of Local Council Tax Support the Government plans to take forward; and when such recommendations will be implemented.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","45164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576744","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-13","<p>Government is committed to making the process of compulsory purchase orders clearer, fairer and faster. The Housing and Planning Act and the Neighbourhood Planning Bill will enable us to lay the legislation to insist that public bodies pay interest on payments of compensation that are paid late. The Regulations to set this level of interest will be laid at least 21 days before the substantive commencement of sections 192 to 198 of the Housing and Planning Act. This is likely to be in spring 2017.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-09-13T14:05:20.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576744/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576744/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-06","Housing and Planning Act 2016","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when the statutory instruments relating to clause 196 of the Housing and Planning Act 2016 will be laid before the House.","false","Biography information for Robert Neill","Bromley and Chislehurst","Robert Neill","45165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576745","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-14","<p>The government made available the summary of responses to the discussion paper &quot;Parking Reform: Tackling Unfair Practices&quot; on 11 May.</p><p>The summary can be found here: http://www.britishparking.co.uk/write/Documents/DCLG_Summary_of_responses_BPA.pdf</p><p>We will set out our proposals on parking reform in due course.</p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy",,"2016-09-14T16:40:17.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576745/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576745/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-06","Parking: Unfair Practices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to publish his Department's response to the Parking Reform: Tackling Unfair Practices consultation.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","45179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576746","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-14","<p>The number of possession hearings that took place in respect of (a) private and (b) social landlords are available on GOV.UK using the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/mortgage-and-landlord-possession-statistics-april-to-june-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/mortgage-and-landlord-possession-statistics-april-to-june-2016</a></p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-09-14T15:43:54.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576746/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576746/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-06","Rented Housing: Evictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what information her Department holds on the number of eviction possession hearings that took place in respect of (a) private and (b) social landlords in the last year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Kevin Hollinrake","Thirsk and Malton","Kevin Hollinrake","45186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576747","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-12","<p>I refer my Honourable friend to the answer to PQ 44837, answered on 7<sup>th</sup> September.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-09-12T16:01:25.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576747/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576747/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576747/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-06","Sportsgrounds: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she is taking to ensure that public-facing staff at sports venues have disability equality awareness training.","false","Biography information for Graham Evans","Weaver Vale","Graham Evans","45081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576748","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-14","<p>The Homeless World Cup is an excellent example of how sport can transform the lives of homeless people all over the country, and we particularly championed the role of Pride House in creating spaces for lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, and intersex people to engage with and celebrate the event.</p><p> </p><p>As outlined in our Sport Strategy, the Government recognises the power of engaging in sport and wants to encourage more people from every background to regularly take part in sport.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-09-14T09:48:26.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576748/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576748/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-06","Football: Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether she was aware of the Homeless World Cup taking place; and what discussions her Department has had with the organisers of that event.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","45138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576749","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","true","2016-09-12","<p>Information on trends in radio listening in the UK is published quarterly by Radio Joint Audience Research (RAJAR). According to RAJAR, digital radio's share of listening continues to grow steadily and digital radio now accounts for 45.3 per cent (Q2 2016) of all radio listening. Around 59 per cent of adults listen to digital radio services at least weekly. <del class="ministerial">Supported by the growth of new commercial digital services, on current trends the radio industry expects digital's share of listening will overtake analogue by the end of 2017. At that point, Government has said it will need to consider the decision about the timetable for any future switch-off of analogue radio services.</del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">Any decision over a timetable for switchover will be taken in due course.</ins></p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-09-12T12:40:54.107Z","2016-09-12T13:06:19.137Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576749/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576749/answer","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576749/answer/previousversion/10416","Biography information for Matt Hancock","10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-06","Digital Broadcasting: Radio","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when her Department estimates that digital radio will reach 50 per cent of listeners; and when she plans to publish a timetable for any switchover beyond that date.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","45111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576750","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Government is supportive of the International Olympic Committee's Agenda approach that honours clean athletes by awarding an Olympic medal following a positive doping case. Formal medal ceremonies are arranged for medal-winners who receive their Olympic medal following the disqualification of a competitor. There is absolutely no place for drug cheats in sport and it is completely right that clean athletes receive medals when tests have proven doping violations.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-09-12T16:12:51.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576750/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576750/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-06","Sports: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions her Department has had with the International Olympic Committee and the British Olympic Association on ensuring that British athletes who placed behind athletes found guilty of doping in competitions have their medals and awards upgraded.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","45128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576751","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-14","<p>The information requested in not available. £121.73m has been made available by the UK Government to fund the roll out of superfast broadband in Scotland.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-09-14T14:33:45.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576751/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576751/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-06","Telecommunications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many premises are connected to exchange activated telephone exchanges; and if she will make funds available to upgrade such exchanges.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","45195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576752","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-13","<p>Through the Government’s investment of over £780 million, superfast broadband is now available to over 90% of homes and businesses in the UK, compared to 45% in 2010. By the end of 2017 it will be available to 95% of homes and businesses. The Government welcomes initiatives taken by local communities and others to support community fibre broadband projects.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-09-13T12:12:59.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576752/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576752/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-06","Broadband: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what support her Department provides to rural communities to install their own fibre networks when commercial and other Government programmes have been unable to reach their premises.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","45196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576753","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-14","<p>In 2015 the then regulator for video on demand services, the Authority for Television on Demand (ATVOD), published its Provision of Video on Demand Access Services Report. The Department analysed the findings of this report, and met with platform operators, content providers and broadcasters to review the provision of such services. The Department has asked broadcasters, content providers and platform operators for a progress update in Spring 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Ofcom is the regulator with responsibility for on-demand programme services (ODPS). Ofcom are presently consulting on how to improve access services and ensure that providers see broadcast and ODPS accessibility as equally important.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-09-14T13:51:19.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576753/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576753/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-06","Video on Demand: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent review her Department has made of the regulatory framework for the provision of subtitles for on-demand services.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","45197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576754","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-13","<p>Most major broadband providers have signed up to Ofcom's Residential Broadband Speeds Code of Practice. This requires providers to give new customers, or customers who have changed their service, information on their guaranteed minimum speed. If a customer cannot get this guaranteed access line speed and providers are unable to resolve the problem, the Code states that providers must allow customers to leave their contract without penalty.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-09-13T12:15:02.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576754/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576754/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-06","Broadband: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether her Department plans to bring forward legislative proposals to prohibit the imposition of broadband service cessation fees by providers who are unable to provide customers with adequate service.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","45192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576755","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-14","<p>There is no agreed definition of ultrafast broadband. According to the independent broadband information website thinkbroadband.com - who define ultrafast as download speeds of more than 100mbps - approximately 50% of UK premises have access to ultrafast broadband.</p><p> </p><p>Virgin Media have announced plans to extend their coverage by up to 4 million premises by 2019 through their Project Lightning roll-out. This roll-out has funding support from the UK Guarantee Scheme which has been put in place the government. BT also plan to make available ultrafast speeds to 10 million premises by 2020. Smaller providers, such as CityFibre, Gigaclear and Hyperoptic, are also investing to provide ultrafast services.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-09-14T15:04:39.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576755/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576755/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576755/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-06","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of UK premises has access to ultrafast broadband; and what steps she is taking to increase the number of such properties.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","45194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576756","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-12","<p>Of the Cyber Essentials certificates issued, around 80% have been to micro, small and medium-sized businesses.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-09-12T11:43:56.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576756/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576756/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576756/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-06","Cybercrime: Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what the level of take-up by (a) micro, (b) small and (c) medium-sized enterprises has been of the Cyber Essentials programme.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","45219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576757","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-12","<p>I refer my honourable friend to my response to PQ 44972, answered on 8<sup>th</sup> September.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-09-12T16:15:41.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576757/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576757/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576757/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-06","Obesity: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what role her Department played in drafting the Government's childhood obesity plan.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","45303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576758","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-14","<p>I refer the honourable member to my response to PQ 44827, answered on 12<sup>th</sup> September.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-09-14T11:02:16.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576758/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576758/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576758/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-06","Nuisance Calls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she is taking to reduce the number of nuisance calls.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","45331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576759","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-12","<p>A: In April 2015 the Government introduced regulations which require authorisation of stakes over £50 on Fixed Odds Betting Terminals (FOBTs) through a “verified account” or staff interaction. The bookmakers shared data with my officials and the Gambling Commission to enable Government to conduct an evaluation of the £50 regulations, published on 21 January. The evaluation can be found here:</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/evaluation-of-gaming-machine-circumstances-of-useamendment-regulations-2015</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Association of British Bookmakers introduced a Code for Responsible Gambling in 2013, updated in 2015, which includes a number of measures relating to FOBTs including the ability to set time and spend limits on gaming machines, the ability to access player statements, and the introduction of Player Awareness Systems which use data analytics to intervene where customers behaviour indicates they may be experiencing problems in their play. The Government meets regularly with industry to discuss player protection measures.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-09-12T16:07:12.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576759/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576759/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576759/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-06","Gaming Machines: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she has taken to work with the gambling industry on the regulation of fixed odds betting terminals.","false","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant","45222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576760","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Government has accepted the case for airport expansion in the South East and the Airports' Commission's shortlisted options. The new Culture Secretary will be ensuring that tourism is one of the factors considered, when a final decision is taken on a preferred scheme.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","44380","2016-09-12T16:11:23.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576760/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576760/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576760/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-06","Heathrow Airport: Tourism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions she has had with Cabinet colleagues on the effect of possible expansion of Heathrow Airport on UK tourism.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","45279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576761","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-12","<p>We are taking forward a range of legislative measures to tackle nuisance calls, which will increase consumer protection and choice by strengthening the Information Commissioner's Office's (ICO) ability to take enforcement action against organisations that break the law. Specific actions include; strengthening the ICO's direct marketing guidance by giving it statutory status; a proposal to extend the ICO’s powers of compulsory audit to more of the organisations that generate nuisance calls; and exploring the options for enabling the ICO to hold company directors to account for breaches of the direct marketing rules.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","44827","2016-09-12T11:46:59.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576761/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576761/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576761/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-06","Nuisance Calls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what further legislative proposals she plans to bring forward to tackle nuisance telephone calls.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","45311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576762","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that people, particularly the young and vulnerable, are protected from the risk of gambling-related harm. We are keeping the issue of advertising, including via social media, under review to ensure that sufficient protections are in place, and will not hesitate to take further action if necessary.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-09-12T16:21:28.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576762/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576762/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576762/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-06","Gambling: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment has she made of the effectiveness of regulations on advertising of gambling products on social media.","false","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant","45223"
