"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576938","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Secretary of State has confirmed that the Government expects to make an announcement on the way forward for supported housing in early autumn.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","45122 ; 45224","2016-09-12T11:34:21.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576938/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576938/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576938/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-06","Supported Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when the Government plans to announce the outcome of its review into future funding for supported housing; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Peter Aldous","Waveney","Peter Aldous","45221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576939","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>This Government is committed to providing a secure and dignified retirement for those pensioners who would otherwise find themselves without an adequate income.</p><p>Pension Credit is an income-related benefit paid out of general taxation which targets help at the poorest pensioners. Pension Credit tops up a person’s other income to a standard minimum amount – currently £155.60 for a single person and £237.55 for a couple. Higher amounts may be available for those with a severe disability, caring responsibilities or certain housing costs. The amount of Pension Credit a person receives depends on how much money they have coming in each week and how much they have saved or invested; regular payments from a charity or relative will generally not count towards this calculation.</p><p>People in receipt of Pension Credit may also qualify for other benefits (each with their own conditions of entitlement) such as Cold Weather Payments, Funeral Payments from the Social Fund and the Warm Home Discount Scheme. Other benefits such as Housing Benefit and help from the Local Council Tax Reduction scheme are available to Pension Credit recipients and to others who may qualify on the grounds of low income.</p><p>Pension Credit recipients are also exempt from certain health charges. Other benefits including Winter Fuel Payments, free prescriptions and concessionary travel are available on the grounds of age.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2016-09-12T14:54:38.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576939/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576939/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576939/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-06","Pensioners: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what support his Department is providing to pensioners who depend on charities and families to pay household bills.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","45139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576940","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>The primary purpose of Carer's Allowance is to provide a measure of financial support and recognition for people who give up the opportunity of full-time employment in order to provide regular and substantial care for a severely disabled person. It is not, and was never intended to be, a carer’s wage or a payment for the services of caring, nor is it intended to replace lost or forgone earnings in their entirety.</p><p> </p><p>The earnings limit for Carer's Allowance is a net figure which is the figure left once income tax, National Insurance contributions and half of any contributions to an occupational or personal pension are deducted from earnings. There are also a number of other deductions which can be made that mean that people can earn significantly more than £110 per week and still be eligible for Carer's Allowance.</p><p> </p><p>Whilst the Government does not link the earnings limit to any other particular factor (including the National Living Wage), we do keep it under regular review and increase it when it is warranted and affordable, and this will continue to be our approach. Most recently in April 2015 the earnings limit was increased by 8% to £110, far outstripping the general increase in earnings.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-09-12T11:54:24.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576940/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576940/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576940/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-06","Carers' Benefits: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect of the living wage on the earnings threshold for carers allowance; and if he will bring forward proposals to raise the existing threshold.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","45121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576941","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Secretary of State has confirmed that the Government expects to make an announcement on the way forward for supported housing in early autumn.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","45221 ; 45224","2016-09-12T11:34:21.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576941/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576941/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576941/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-06","Housing Benefit: Refuges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department plans to exempt domestic violence refuges from proposals to cap housing benefit.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","45122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576942","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>Refugees and people in Great Britain with humanitarian protection status who are disabled and in need of financial support are entitled to claim Disability Living Allowance, providing they meet all the necessary conditions of entitlement set out in regulations.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-09-12T10:39:53.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576942/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576942/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576942/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-06","Disability Living Allowance: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what guidance his Department plans to issue to its staff on the application of residency tests to refugees applying for disability living allowance.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","45160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576943","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-13","<p>The Government set out our assessment of the impact of the welfare policies in the Welfare Reform and Work Act on 20 July 2015, with similar assessments for previous changes.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-09-13T13:57:50.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576943/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576943/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576943/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-06","Social Security Benefits: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an assessment of the effect of the Government's welfare reforms on deprivation in (a) Glasgow East constituency, (b) the city of Glasgow and (c) Scotland.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","45084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576944","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-13","<p>The Department does not hold the information requested. National Trading Standards issues annual reports setting out annual data but it is not broken down into the categories requested.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-09-13T15:24:42.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576944/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576944/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576944/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-06","Motor Vehicles: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many (a) investigations and (b) prosecutions overseen by Trading Standards have related to (i) the mis-selling of vehicles and (ii) the tampering of mileage on vehicles in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","45092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576945","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-27","<p>The Government recently consulted on proposals to increase the amount that energy companies pay to fund household energy efficiency improvements for low income and vulnerable households to £450m by 2017 and up to £640m by 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Energy companies are also required to provide over 2 million low income and vulnerable households with a £140 rebate off their energy bill each winter, under the Warm Home Discount Scheme.</p><p> </p><p>These proposals combined will see up to £1bn of support for low income and vulnerable households each year from 2018.</p><p> </p><p>If suppliers believe a domestic customer is having difficulty paying all or part of their energy bills, they must offer facilities to make payments by: deductions direct from benefits, known as Fuel Direct; regular instalments paid through a means other than a prepayment meter; or, using a prepayment meter, where it is safe and reasonably practicable for the customer to do so.</p><p> </p><p>It is important that customers who are experiencing difficulties in paying their gas or electricity bills contact their supplier as soon as possible to arrange a repayment plan that suits their needs.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-09-27T10:27:13.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576945/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576945/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576945/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-06","Fuel Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to incentivise energy companies to assist people in (a) fuel poverty and (b) fuel debt.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","45093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576946","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-09","<p>The Government is requiring energy suppliers, as part of their licence conditions, to take all reasonable steps to roll-out smart meters to all their domestic and smaller non-domestic customers by 31 December 2020. Good progress is being made with more than 3.6 million meters now operating under the Programme.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-09-09T14:43:04.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576946/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576946/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576946/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-06","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when his Department plans to complete the roll-out of smart meters.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","45091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576947","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-19","<p>Government investment in all forms of renewable energy continues to be predicated on achieving an energy mix that is secure, clean and affordable. Government will be announcing details of the next energy innovation programme and the Contracts for Difference (CfD) allocation round in due course.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-09-19T09:44:07.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576947/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576947/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576947/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-06","Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will make it his policy to continue to support Government investment in (a) new energy sources and (b) tidal energy.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","45145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576948","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Department leads on the Government’s clear commitment to tackle climate change. Many teams deliver against multiple cross cutting objectives</p><p>Consequently, it is not possible to give an exact figure of the number of staff involved in this work. However, the Government has been clear in the need to meet our remission reduction targets while keeping our energy supply secure and low cost.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-09-12T16:17:06.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576948/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576948/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576948/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-06","Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many officials in his Department are working on climate change policy; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","45149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576949","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-10","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given to him by my hon. Friend the Minister for Small Business, Consumers and Corporate Responsibility on 18 July 2016, UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-07-18/43020/" target="_blank">43020</a>.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-10-10T15:03:30.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576949/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576949/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576949/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-06","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of his Department's budget in each of the next three years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","45185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576950","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-15","<p>Solar continues to be deployed under the Feed-in Tariff scheme, with over 140 MW of applications since the scheme reopened in February.</p><p>Changes to the scheme were introduced in 2016 to manage costs and ensure value for money.</p><p>While it is appropriate to allow for a period of stability following these changes, my rt. Hon. Friend the Secretary of State continues to keep the performance of the scheme under review.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-09-15T14:46:34.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576950/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576950/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576950/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-06","Solar Power: Feed-in Tariffs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he plans to take to improve the performance of the Feed-in Tariff scheme for solar power.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","45178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576951","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Nuclear Decommissioning Authority’s (NDA’s) strategy was last updated and published in April of 2016. Progress is monitored in the NDA’s annual report and accounts, supplemented with quarterly progress reports on its business plan, as well as regular updates for priority programmes and major projects. All these documents are available on the NDA’s website.</p><p> </p><p>Some of the highlights include good progress on priority projects, such as regular retrieval of waste from legacy facilities at Sellafield, removal of all spent nuclear fuel from the Oldbury nuclear power station and the ongoing defueling of the nuclear power station at Wylfa on Anglesey following its closure in December 2015.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-09-12T09:20:47.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576951/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576951/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576951/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-06","Radioactive Waste","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent progress has been made on the accelerated decommissioning programme for nuclear waste in the UK.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","45307"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576952","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-12","<p>Under the terms of the contract, which has yet to be entered into, the remaining total cost to the public purse for the construction at Hinkley Point C would be borne entirely by the developer, who would bear all the construction risk. If construction comes in under budget then any savings above a threshold would be shared with consumers, but if there are overspends then the developer would bear any additional costs.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-09-12T12:44:06.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576952/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576952/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576952/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-06","Hinkley Point C Power Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the remaining total cost to the public purse will be of construction at Hinkley Point C should that project receive approval.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","45306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576953","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-13","<p>The Airports Commission shortlisted three airport expansion schemes, two at Heathrow and one at Gatwick. The Government accepted the Commission’s shortlist in December 2015 and is considering all of the evidence very carefully before reaching a view on its preferred scheme. The Government is not providing a running commentary on this work before an announcement on its preference.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-13T09:37:20.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576953/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576953/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576953/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-06","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effect that a possible Heathrow Airport expansion will have on UK industry.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","45281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576954","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-13","<p>The UK’s generous entitlement of 52 weeks’ maternity leave provides mothers with sufficient leave to take account of a range of circumstances. Parents who have been employees with the same employer for over a year also have a separate entitlement to parental leave of 18 weeks per parent per child, up to the child’s 18<sup>th</sup> birthday, of which typically up to 4 weeks can be taken in one year.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-09-13T15:16:56.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576954/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576954/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576954/answer","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576954/answer/previousversion/10925","Biography information for Margot James","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-06","Maternity Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent assessment he has made of the potential merits of extending the period of maternity leave for mothers of premature babies.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","45213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576955","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-12","<p>I refer the Rt hon Member to the reply I gave to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-09-05/44973/" target="_blank">44973</a>.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-09-12T10:48:47.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576955/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576955/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576955/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-06","Children: Obesity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what role his Department played in drafting the Government's childhood obesity plan.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","45304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576956","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-12","<p>We remain committed to making Britain the best place in Europe to own and grow a business. That includes supporting those businesses that trade with the EU and the wider international markets, as well as continuing to encourage record foreign direct investment which supports business and communities up and down the country. Through our industrial strategy we will continue to put power in the hands of local communities to drive economic growth working in partnership with local business and civic leaders – to deliver an economy that works for all.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-09-12T09:20:11.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576956/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576956/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576956/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-06","Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effect of the UK leaving the EU on the renewables industry in (a) Northern Ireland and (b) the rest of the UK.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","45305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576957","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-12","<p>Security of nuclear waste is a high priority for the Government, and the Office for Nuclear Regulation provides independent assurance that materials are kept safely and securely. The spending review settlement for the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority also supports continuing investment in security infrastructure. However the Government does not comment on security measures at nuclear sites.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-09-12T09:21:49.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576957/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576957/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576957/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-06","Radioactive Waste","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to improve security measures at sites containing nuclear waste.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","45308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576958","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-12","<p>The continued use of unabated coal for power generation is not consistent with our policy of decarbonising the economy. The role of coal for electricity generation has declined rapidly in the last couple of years due to the success of the Government’s policies to penalise emissions of carbon dioxide and other pollutants and encourage investment in lower carbon alternatives.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-09-12T12:44:29.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576958/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576958/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576958/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-06","Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to the speech of the then Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change on 18 November 2015, on a new direction for UK energy policy, when the terms of reference of the review into coal will be published; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","45332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576959","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-14","<p>Draft 2017 rateable values prepared independently by the Valuation Office Agency will be published for the first time on 30 September 2016. Once rateable values are available we will look closely at the impacts of the forthcoming revaluation and consult on how to make sure the right support is in place for businesses to adjust to any changes.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-09-14T16:41:23.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576959/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576959/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576959/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-06","Solar Power: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of recent changes in business rates on corporate demand for rooftop solar power.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","45169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576960","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-12","<p>Business rates are based on valuations from the Valuation Office Agency and we do not intervene in their independent assessments. We will look closely at the impacts of the forthcoming revaluation and consult on how to make sure the right support is in place for businesses to adjust to any changes.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-09-12T15:45:47.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576960/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576960/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576960/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-06","Solar Power: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what representations his Department has made to the Valuation Office Agency on the effect of planned business rate increases for solar power on the solar industry.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","45250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576961","Department for International Trade","false","2016-09-13","<p>Following her appointment on 13 July 2016 the Prime Minister established the Department for International Trade (DIT). The DIT aggregates UK Trade and Investment (UKTI), UK Export and Finance (UKEF), Trade Policy Units from the Department for Business, Energy &amp; Industrial Strategy (BEIS), as well as some new hires.</p><p>Until such time as a transfer of functions order establishes the Secretary of State as a corporation sole, DIT remains a unified Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) and Department for Business, Energy &amp; Industrial Strategy (BEIS) department for accounting purposes.</p><p>As DIT is currently being formed, the number staff the Department employs is being finalised while employee transfers and recruitment are taking place.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-09-13T16:46:04.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576961/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576961/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576961/answer","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576961/answer/previousversion/11182","Biography information for Greg Hands","202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-09-06","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many staff at what civil service grades his Department employs.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","45238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576962","Department for International Trade","false","2016-09-12","<p>As part of their official duties, since 14 July 2016, Ministers have taken 22 flights overseas and accompanying officials have taken 25 flights overseas.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-09-12T15:40:06.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576962/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576962/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576962/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-09-06","Department for International Trade: Travel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many flights (a) Ministers and (b) officials of his Department have taken as part of their official duties since his Department was set up on 14 July 2016.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","45236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576963","Department for International Trade","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Prime Minister has established the Department for International Trade to promote British trade across the world, and to ensure the UK takes advantage of all the opportunities open to us. We are actively engaging with a broad range of international partners to discuss our trading relationships. Earlier this week my rt hon. Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade met with the Australian Minister for Trade and Investment and the Prime Minister had a number of productive discussions with partners at the G20 summit in Hangzhou. We will continue this engagement to best promote British trade, and to ensure that Britain becomes the global leader in free trade.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-09-12T15:06:30.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576963/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576963/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576963/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-09-06","Department for International Trade: Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, on what trade deals his Department has begun the negotiation process; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","45314"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576964","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-13","<p>Evidence on the links between long-haul air connections and international trade was presented by the Airports Commission in its Final Report and supporting documents. The Government is considering all of this evidence very carefully.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-13T09:39:42.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576964/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576964/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576964/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-06","Aviation: Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the importance of direct long-haul air links with a hub airport when opening trade discussions around the world.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","45280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576965","Department for International Trade","false","2016-09-14","<p>My Rt Hon. Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade met with the Japanese Ambassador to the United Kingdom on 6 September. A range of topics were discussed including the opportunities presented by the United Kingdom exiting the European Union to strengthen its role as a global leader for free trade, including its trade links with Japan.</p><p> </p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-09-14T14:06:26.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576965/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576965/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576965/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-09-06","Overseas Trade: Japan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what discussions he has had with the government of Japan on increasing trade links with that country.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","45204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576966","Department for International Trade","false","2016-09-13","<p>As the Prime Minister made clear earlier this week, as we leave the EU, Britain will seek to become the global leader in free trade. This is why my team of Ministers and officials at the Department for International Trade are actively engaging with our international partners. Through these discussions, we are working to best promote British trade, and to ensure we take advantage of the great opportunities available to us – including through our future trading relationships.</p><p> </p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-09-13T16:15:54.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576966/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576966/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576966/answer","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576966/answer/previousversion/11183","Biography information for Mark Garnier","202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-09-06","Department for International Trade: Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many meetings have been held between Ministers of his Department and their international counterparts on future trade deals since his Department was created; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","45148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576967","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-12","<p>The new Department for Exiting the European Union will be made up of staff and officials from various departments across Government. The Department has already started drawing together expertise from a wide range of departments where there is specific relevant knowledge.</p><p>The overall size and scope of the Department, including staffing and budget, are now under consideration. The Department now has over 200 staff in London, plus the expertise of over 120 officials in Brussels, and is still growing rapidly with first class support from other government departments.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-09-12T16:05:39.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576967/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576967/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576967/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-09-06","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many staff his Department (a) employs and (b) plans to employ in the next 12 months; and how many such staff will be located in (i) London, (ii) Brussels and (iii) elsewhere.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","45150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576968","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-12","<p>The new Department for Exiting the European Union is properly resourced. Detailed work is underway to establish the final budget required to fulfil the Department’s set-up and responsibilities. The budget of the Department will be set out to the House and approved as part of the supplementary estimates in the new year, as is standard practice.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-09-12T16:57:45.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576968/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576968/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576968/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-09-06","Department for Exiting the European Union: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what estimate he has made of the budget of his Department in each of the next three years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","45147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576969","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-15","<p>My Department is working closely with the Home Office and other Government Departments to identify and develop options to shape our future immigration system, including considering how best to control the number of people coming to the UK from the following Brexit. We are already fully engaged with the Governments of Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland to ensure a UK-wide approach to our negotiations. My ministerial collegues and I have also discussed the next steps with a range of organisations, including the General Secretary of the Trades Union Congress and key business groups.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-09-15T16:22:54.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576969/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576969/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576969/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-09-06","Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what recent steps he has taken to decide the immigration system to be implemented upon the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","45324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576970","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-14","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy is working with industry organisations and interests across Government. This input will inform our the Government’s approach as we shape our future relationship with Europe.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-09-14T13:17:22.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576970/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576970/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576970/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576970/answer/previousversion/11062","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-06","Qualifications: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what his policy is on retaining the EU's professional qualifications directive after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","45313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576971","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-15","<p>The Prime Minister has made it clear that we will not be triggering Article 50 before the end of 2016. She has said that we won't be triggering Article 50 until we have a UK approach and clear objectives for negotiations. It is in everyone's interest that we establish this before we trigger Article 50.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-09-15T15:49:55.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576971/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576971/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576971/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-09-06","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, when he plans for the UK to initiate Article 50; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","45218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576972","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-14","<p>We are yet to begin our negotiations to withdraw from the European Union and it would be wrong to set out unilateral positions in advance. At every step of these negotiations we will work to ensure the best possible outcome for the UK.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-09-14T16:35:37.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576972/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576972/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576972/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-06","Electronic Commerce","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what his policy is on future collaboration with the EU on consumer protections in relation to e-commerce; if he will make it his policy to ensure UK consumers who access e-commerce firms located in the EU single market continue to be offered the protections currently provided by the Directive on Consumer Rights of 25 October 2011 (2011/83/EC).","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","45265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576973","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-13","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the answer given to her by my Hon. Friend the Minister of State for Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (written question 43718).</p><p>The EU-wide ban on keeping hens in ‘battery’ (conventional) cages in 2012 represented a significant welfare advance across the EU, was supported by the UK and has been implemented in full. The Government has a manifesto commitment to protect farm animal welfare and to push for high animal welfare standards to be incorporated into farming policy.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-09-13T15:34:48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576973/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576973/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576973/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-09-06","Poultry: Animal Welfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, if he will make it his policy to ensure the UK maintains the requirements of Council Directive 1999/74/EC on battery hens.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","45267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576974","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-09-14","<p>Across the UK, agriculture will receive the same level of funding that it would have received under the Common Agricultural Policy until at least the end of the Multi-Annual Financial Framework in 2020, even if the UK leaves the EU before this point.</p><p> </p><p>The UK Government will be working closely with the devolved administrations as we work on future agriculture policy.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-09-14T11:47:48.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576974/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576974/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576974/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-09-06","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what her policy is on the devolution of the policy and administration of agricultural subsidies to the devolved administrations once the UK exits the Common Agricultural Policy.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","45268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576975","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-16","<p>We are leaving the EU but co-operation on security with our European and global allies will be maintained. We will do what is necessary to keep our people safe - our aim will be to continue cooperation where it is in the national interest to protect the public. We are about to begin these negotiations and it would be wrong to set out unilateral positions in advance.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","45271 ; 45272","2016-09-16T10:03:07.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576975/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576975/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576975/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-09-06","Europol","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what his policy is on future UK membership of Europol.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","45269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576976","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-16","<p>We are leaving the EU but co-operation on security with our European and global allies will be maintained. We will do what is necessary to keep our people safe - our aim will be to continue cooperation where it is in the national interest to protect the public. We are about to begin these negotiations and it would be wrong to set out unilateral positions in advance.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","45269 ; 45271","2016-09-16T10:03:07.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576976/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576976/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576976/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-09-06","Police: Cross Border Cooperation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, if he will make it his policy to continue UK access to the Schengen Information System for law enforcement purposes once the UK exits the EU.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","45272"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576977","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-12","<p>We are leaving the EU but co-operation on security, including on cyber security, with our European and global allies will be undiminished. We will do what is necessary to keep our people safe. We are about to begin these negotiations and it would be wrong to set out unilateral positions in advance.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-09-12T15:40:01.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576977/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576977/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576977/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-09-06","Cybercrime: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what his policy is on future UK participation in the EU cybersecurity strategy.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","45273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576978","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-16","<p>We are leaving the EU but co-operation on security with our European and global allies will be maintained. We will do what is necessary to keep our people safe - our aim will be to continue cooperation where it is in the national interest to protect the public. We are about to begin these negotiations and it would be wrong to set out unilateral positions in advance.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","45269 ; 45272","2016-09-16T10:03:07.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576978/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576978/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576978/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-09-06","European Arrest Warrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what his policy is on future UK involvement in the European Arrest Warrant.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","45271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576987","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-15","<p>The Government has provided information in order for all individuals to be able to find out their State Pension age and conditions of their benefits. For example, following the Pensions Act 1995, State Pension estimates, issued to individuals on request, made the changes clear.</p><p> </p><p>Following the 2011 changes, which brought about faster equalisation of men’s and women’s State Pension ages and accelerated the timetable for the rise to 66, DWP wrote to all individuals directly affected to inform them of the change to their State Pension age, using the address details recorded by HMRC at the time.</p><p> </p><p>Information on State Pension age changes and who they affect is also available on <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a>, and the online State Pension age calculator gives individuals a quick and simple way to check when they will reach State Pension age.</p><p> </p><p>As part of a national advertising campaign about the changes to the State Pension from 6 April 2016, we encouraged people to find out about their State Pension age. Between August 2015 and April 2016, there were 1.6m visits to the campaign page GOV.UK/yourstatepension. Between February 2016 and April 2016 the State Pension age calculator was used 2.3 million times. The campaign directs people to our new online Check your State Pension service where individual personal State Pension forecasts can be viewed. Over a million forecasts have been viewed since the service launched in February 2016.</p><p> </p><p>We have committed to completing a review of the State Pension age by May 2017. As part of our on-going no-cost media activity on the issue, the launch of the review, for example, was the front page of a number of national newspapers.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-09-15T11:43:04.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576987/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576987/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576987/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-06","State Retirement Pensions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what efforts they have made to inform people what their individual state pension age will be (1) directly using individual letters, and (2) indirectly such as through a national high-profile advertising campaign.","false","Biography information for Baroness Altmann",,"Baroness Altmann","HL1584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576988","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-15","<p>The information requested is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate costs.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-09-15T11:46:14.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576988/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576988/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576988/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-06","State Retirement Pensions: Females","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many letters the Department for Work and Pensions has received from Members of Parliament since May 2015 on behalf of women who have complained about the impact of an increase in their state pension age.","false","Biography information for Baroness Altmann",,"Baroness Altmann","HL1585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576989","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-19","<p>The Government does not collect data on the number of workers earning less than the personal allowance who are also members of pension schemes that operate a net pay system. The Government does not hold employee level data on employees enrolled in net pay pension schemes, as such schemes are not obliged to report pension contributions to HM Revenue and Customs. The Government does not therefore hold information on the value of tax reliefs paid out to employees in net pay schemes.</p><p> </p><p>However, the Pensions Regulator provides guidance to employers on choosing a pension scheme for their staff in order to discharge their statutory obligations under automatic enrolment. This guidance covers the choice between net pay and relief at source schemes, and the implications of net pay schemes for employees who do not pay tax.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL1587 ; HL1589 ; HL1757","2016-09-19T09:17:28.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576989/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576989/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576989/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-06","Occupational Pensions: Tax Allowances","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many workers earning below the personal tax threshold were paying into net-pay pension schemes in (1) 2010–11, (2) 2011–12, (3) 2012–13, (4) 2013–14, (5) 2014–15, (6) 2015–16 and (7) 2016–17 to date.","false","Biography information for Baroness Altmann",,"Baroness Altmann","HL1586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576990","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-19","<p>The Government does not collect data on the number of workers earning less than the personal allowance who are also members of pension schemes that operate a net pay system. The Government does not hold employee level data on employees enrolled in net pay pension schemes, as such schemes are not obliged to report pension contributions to HM Revenue and Customs. The Government does not therefore hold information on the value of tax reliefs paid out to employees in net pay schemes.</p><p> </p><p>However, the Pensions Regulator provides guidance to employers on choosing a pension scheme for their staff in order to discharge their statutory obligations under automatic enrolment. This guidance covers the choice between net pay and relief at source schemes, and the implications of net pay schemes for employees who do not pay tax.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL1586 ; HL1589 ; HL1757","2016-09-19T09:17:29.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576990/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576990/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576990/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-06","Occupational Pensions: Tax Allowances","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the number of workers who earn under £11,000 a year and are contributing to net-pay pension schemes.","false","Biography information for Baroness Altmann",,"Baroness Altmann","HL1587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576991","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-15","<p>Pensions’ taxation is a matter for Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs.</p><p> </p><p>The noble Baroness may, however, find it helpful to note that the Pensions Regulator’s website provides comprehensive guidance for employers about their duties under workplace pensions’ legislation. This guidance covers pension scheme choice and the implications for an employer’s workforce of net-pay arrangements and relief-at-source schemes.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-09-15T11:43:31.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576991/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576991/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576991/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-06","Occupational Pensions: Tax Allowances","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action the Department for Work and Pensions has taken to inform employers and pension scheme members of the implications for those on low pay of using a net-pay scheme rather than a relief-at-source scheme that adds the tax relief due.","false","Biography information for Baroness Altmann",,"Baroness Altmann","HL1588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576992","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-19","<p>The Government does not collect data on the number of workers earning less than the personal allowance who are also members of pension schemes that operate a net pay system. The Government does not hold employee level data on employees enrolled in net pay pension schemes, as such schemes are not obliged to report pension contributions to HM Revenue and Customs. The Government does not therefore hold information on the value of tax reliefs paid out to employees in net pay schemes.</p><p> </p><p>However, the Pensions Regulator provides guidance to employers on choosing a pension scheme for their staff in order to discharge their statutory obligations under automatic enrolment. This guidance covers the choice between net pay and relief at source schemes, and the implications of net pay schemes for employees who do not pay tax.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL1586 ; HL1587 ; HL1757","2016-09-19T09:17:29.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576992/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576992/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576992/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-06","Occupational Pensions: Tax Allowances","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the number of employers using net-pay pension schemes that are unaware that their workers who earn less than £11,000 a year are unable to receive the tax relief they could receive in a relief-at-source scheme.","false","Biography information for Baroness Altmann",,"Baroness Altmann","HL1589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576993","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-19","<p>As members of the Peace Implementation Council, the UK issued a statement on 30 August 2016 urging the Republika Srpska authorities not to hold the proposed referendum and making clear our support for the High Representative. The Government is in close contact with the High Representative and international partners about the proposed referendum and is committed to upholding the territorial integrity and structure of Bosnia and Herzegovina (BiH) as a single, sovereign state comprising two entities.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-19T09:48:31.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576993/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576993/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576993/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-06","Bosnia and Herzegovina: Sovereignty","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, ahead of the referendum in the entity of Republika Srpska on 25 September, what support they have given High Representative Valentin Inzko to enable him to exercise his mandate under the Dayton Peace Accord to uphold the territorial integrity and sovereignty of Bosnia and Herzegovina.","false","Biography information for Baroness Helic",,"Baroness Helic","HL1590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576994","Department for International Development","false","2016-09-20","<p>The Syria Conference raised a record amount of more than $12 billion - the largest amount raised in one day for a humanitarian crisis. $6billion was pledged for 2016 and a further $6.1billion for 2017-20 to enable partners to plan ahead. According to the UN, as of 26 August, $4.8 billion has been committed by donors to implementing partners for humanitarian assistance in 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The UK continues to urge donors to deliver on the commitments made in London including at the forthcoming UN General Assembly in New York, where the Secretary of State for International Development will co-host a Conference follow-up event. The Department for International Development has set up a tracking mechanism that will report on the delivery of all the financial commitments made at the conference, including humanitarian and development funding and loans. The first report from the tracking mechanism will be published in September.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-20T11:51:15.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576994/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576994/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576994/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-09-06","Syria: Humanitarian Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much of the $6 billion of humanitarian aid pledged at the Supporting Syria and the Region conference in February has been disbursed.","false","Biography information for Baroness Helic",,"Baroness Helic","HL1591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576995","Department for International Development","false","2016-09-20","<p>The Syria Conference raised a record amount of more than $12 billion - the largest amount raised in one day for a humanitarian crisis. This was supported by Multilateral Development Banks and donors’ pledges of around $41 billion loans, including $1.7 billion on highly concessional terms.</p><p> </p><p>The World Bank launched the MENA Finance Initiative to support Syrian refugees and host communities in Jordan and Lebanon at the Spring Meetings in April. Donors pledged $140 million in grants and over $1 billion in concessional loans. Grant pledges have since increased to $225 million.</p><p> </p><p>As part of this initiative, the UK is providing an £80 million concessional loan to the World Bank MENA Finance Facility to support employment opportunities for Syrian refugees in Jordan. In July, a successful first meeting of the Steering Committee saw two Jordan projects approved.</p><p> </p><p>The UK continues to urge donors to deliver on the commitments made at the London Conference in London. The Department for International Development has set up a tracking mechanism that will report on the delivery of the financial commitments made at the London Conference, including humanitarian and development funding and loans. The first report from the tracking mechanism will be published in September.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-20T11:49:18.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576995/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576995/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576995/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-09-06","Syria: Foreign Loans","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress has been made since the Supporting Syria and the Region conference in February in implementing loans by multilateral development banks and bilateral donors to help vulnerable Syrians and host communities in the Middle East.","false","Biography information for Baroness Helic",,"Baroness Helic","HL1592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576996","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-13","<p>On current plans, the refit for HMS LANCASTER will commence in mid 2017 and the refit for HMS DAUNTLESS is scheduled for the end of 2017.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-09-13T15:51:03.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576996/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576996/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576996/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-06","Warships: Repairs and Maintenance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when the refits of HMS Dauntless and HMS Lancaster will commence.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL1593"
