he dental practice providing training &amp; facilities.</p><p>2. Trainee Salary/Maintenance cost is the contribution to the trainee salary and associated costs.</p><p> </p><p>Table C</p><p>Cost to HEE of providing dental foundation training in primary care</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Dental foundation training salary</p></td><td><p>£31,044</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Dental foundation trainer grant</p></td><td><p>£9,324</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Service costs</p></td><td><p>£64,164</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>£104,532</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p>1. Training salary is the reimbursement of the salary paid to the dental trainee.</p><p>2. Trainer grant is the sum that represents the time spent in supervising a trainee.</p><p>3. Service costs is a sum that represents the service costs of employing a trainee.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL1482","2016-09-16T10:51:04.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576243/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576243/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576243/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-05","Dentistry: Training","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the average cost to the public purse of providing a foundation training place for a dental graduate.","false","Biography information for Lord Colwyn",,"Lord Colwyn","HL1483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576244","Department for Education","false","2016-09-16","<p>The issue of asbestos in schools is a serious one and the government is supporting those that are legally responsible for managing asbestos in schools.</p><p> </p><p>The Health and Safety Executive, which is the lead regulator on managing asbestos advise that as long as asbestos is in good condition and unlikely to be damaged or disturbed, it is not a significant risk to health to pupils and students during the course of their daily activities. On this basis, the department has provided targeted guidance to schools on the effective management of asbestos in their schools and has recently concluded a voluntary data collection exercise to understand how duty holders are managing asbestos in their schools.</p><p> </p><p>The department directly funds the removal of asbestos through schemes such as the Priority Schools Building Programme and provides capital funding for asbestos management and removal where appropriate for those schools that have identified that asbestos is in poor condition or poses a high risk of deterioration.</p><p> </p><p>The department is not committing to the removal of asbestos in all schools as blanket and accelerated removal of asbestos in schools is potentially more dangerous and may involve greater risk to school children and staff.</p><p> </p><p>It is the aim of the government that, over time, as more school buildings are replaced and refurbished, all asbestos will be removed from schools.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-09-16T09:32:55.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576244/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576244/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576244/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-09-05","Schools: Asbestos","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to eradicate the presence of asbestos on school sites in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Baroness Donaghy",,"Baroness Donaghy","HL1484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576245","Home Office","false","2016-09-16","<p>Our records currently indicate that since Royal Assent, 30 children who meet the criteria in the Immigration Act 2016 have been transferred to the UK. Details on the European country these children arrived from are not currently available. This is provisional management information that is subject to change. It has not been assured to the standard of Official Statistics.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-09-16T13:04:31.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576245/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576245/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576245/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-05","Refugees: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many unaccompanied child refugees have been transferred to the UK under the terms of the Immigration Act 2016 from (1) France, (2) Italy, and (3) Greece.","false","Biography information for Lord Dubs",,"Lord Dubs","HL1485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576246","Home Office","false","2016-09-16","<p>Our records currently indicate that in 2016 the Government has transferred just under 100 unaccompanied refugee children to the UK under the Dublin Regulation, the majority of which are from France. This is provisional management information that is subject to change. It has not been assured to the standard of Official Statistics.</p><p>In 2015, around 20 unaccompanied refugee children in Europe were accepted for transfer to the UK.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-09-16T13:03:51.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576246/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576246/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576246/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-05","Refugees: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many child refugees have been transferred to the UK because they had an existing family connection in the UK from (1) France, (2) Greece, and (3) Italy, in (a) 2015, and (b) 2016 to date.","false","Biography information for Lord Dubs",,"Lord Dubs","HL1486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576247","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Department for Transport publishes estimates of the average cost to society of road traffic accidents as part of the Transport Analysis Guidance (called WebTAG). The cost is broken down into six elements. Three of these elements are casualty-related:</p><ul><li>lost output/cost to the economy</li><li>medical and ambulance costs</li><li>human costs</li></ul><p> </p><p>The remaining three are accident-related:</p><ul><li>police costs</li><li>insurance and administration costs</li><li>damage to property</li></ul><p> </p><p>The human cost element is estimated using evidence of individuals’ willingness to pay for a marginal reduction in their risk of suffering a road traffic accident. The other components are estimated using official data sources.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has not made any estimate of the costs of road traffic accidents to the justice system or the benefits system. However, it is likely that these will be small in comparison with human and lost output costs.</p><p> </p><p>The table below gives an estimate of the costs for each of the six WebTAG elements for all reported personal-injury accidents in Great Britain where at least one driver was over the alcohol limit. The figures are based on accidents that occurred in 2014 as this is the most recent year for which final drink drive accident statistics are available. The totals are in 2016 prices.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Total value of prevention of reported accidents when at least one driver is over the alcohol limit, Great Britain, 2014</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p>£million in 2016 prices</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Accident severity</p></td><td><p>Police costs</p></td><td><p>Insurance and admin</p></td><td><p>Damage to property</p></td><td><p>Lost output</p></td><td><p>Human costs</p></td><td><p>Medical and ambulance</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Fatal</p></td><td><p>4.4</p></td><td><p>0.1</p></td><td><p>2.7</p></td><td><p>150.6</p></td><td><p>287.3</p></td><td><p>0.3</p></td><td><p>445.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Serious</p></td><td><p>2.1</p></td><td><p>0.2</p></td><td><p>4.9</p></td><td><p>25.9</p></td><td><p>178.0</p></td><td><p>15.7</p></td><td><p>226.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Slight</p></td><td><p>2.7</p></td><td><p>0.6</p></td><td><p>15.0</p></td><td><p>17.6</p></td><td><p>84.0</p></td><td><p>7.5</p></td><td><p>127.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>799.5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-09-12T14:44:50.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576247/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576247/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576247/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-05","Driving under Influence","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimates they have made of the costs of road traffic accidents associated with alcohol to (1) the NHS, (2) the emergency services, (3) the police, (4) the justice system, (5) the benefits system, and (6) individual victims.","false","Biography information for Baroness Finlay of Llandaff",,"Baroness Finlay of Llandaff","HL1487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576248","Department of Health","false","2016-09-13","<p>The last meeting of the Public Health Responsibility Deal Alcohol Network was held on 5 November 2014. A copy of the minutes from the meeting is attached.</p><p> </p><p>Following that meeting, on 6 November 2014, the Department published the results of the independent Campden BRI report on the Responsibility Deal labelling pledge. This showed that by the end of 2013, 79.3% of labels of bottles and cans of alcoholic drinks displayed unit content, the previous Chief Medical Officer’s lower-risk drinking guidelines and a warning about drinking when pregnant. On 19 December 2014 the Department also published the results of the monitoring of the Responsibility Deal pledge to remove 1 billion units of alcohol from the market by the end of 2015. This showed that the target had been exceeded by 0.3 billion units and was met two years ahead of schedule.</p><p> </p><p>There are currently no plans for a further meeting of the Responsibility Deal Alcohol Network. However, the Government remains committed to partnership working.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-09-13T16:34:55.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576248/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576248/answer","HL1488 - Notes_RDAN-meeting-5-November-2014.pdf","HL1488 - Notes_RDAN-meeting-5-November-2014.pdf","RDAN MEETING 2014","RDAN MEETING 2014","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576248/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-05","Responsibility Deal Alcohol Network","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when the last meeting of the Public Health Responsibility Deal Alcohol Network was held, what actions have been taken since that meeting, and when the next meeting is scheduled to take place.","false","Biography information for Baroness Finlay of Llandaff",,"Baroness Finlay of Llandaff","HL1488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576249","Department of Health","false","2016-09-16","<p>In April 2016, NHS England updated its guidance <em>Commissioning Person Centred End of Life Care: A Toolkit for Health and Social Care</em>. This document highlighted that fundamental to any commissioning plan for end of life care is a local strategy, jointly developed with local people and key partners, clearly setting out a vision for end of life and palliative care. Included in this are examples of how working with third sector organisations can benefit service provision for palliative care services, as well as links to guidance from these organisations. A copy of the toolkit is attached.</p><p>In addition, <em>Our Commitment to you for end of life care</em> published on 5 July 2016, highlighted that the Department will work with the National Partnership for Palliative and End of Life Care and the End of Life Care Coalition of charities to promote the implementation of the Ambitions for Palliative and End of Life Care Framework in local areas. A copy of the report is attached.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-09-16T11:04:21.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576249/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576249/answer","nhsiq-comms-eolc-tlkit-.pdf ; choice-response.pdf","nhsiq-comms-eolc-tlkit-.pdf ; choice-response.pdf","Toolkit ; Government Response","Toolkit ; Government Response","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576249/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-05","Palliative Care","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to provide guidance to Clinical Commissioning Groups on working with charities to provide comprehensive palliative care services for patients of all ages; and if so, when.","false","Biography information for Baroness Finlay of Llandaff",,"Baroness Finlay of Llandaff","HL1489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576250","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-15","<p>The Government is considering a number of issues related to the Building Regulations 2010 and building control system matters in England. We will make an announcement about our plans in due course.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-09-15T13:59:32.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576250/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576250/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576250/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-05","Building Regulations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to review the guidance issued under the Building Regulations 2010, in particular that guidance relating to fire safety.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL1490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576251","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>Data from the Fire Incident Recording System are published by financial year. There were 216, 195 and 229 fire-related fatalities in dwellings in England in financial years 2013-14, 2014-15 and 2015-16 respectively. The latest figures were published in August in the Fire Statistics Monitor, which can be found here https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fire-statistics-monitor-april-2015-to-march-2016 while detailed tables can be found here https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-09-12T14:52:49.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576251/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576251/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576251/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-05","Housing: Fires","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many domestic fire deaths were recorded in (1) 2013, (2) 2014, and (3) 2015.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL1491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576252","Home Office","false","2016-09-16","<p>Data from the Fire Incident Recording System are published by financial year.</p><p>(1) Fire and rescue services attended 31,899, 31,329 and 31,333 dwelling fires in England in financial years 2013-14, 2014-15 and 2015-16 respectively.</p><p>Dwelling fires are fires in properties that are a place of residence i.e. places occupied by households such as houses and flats, excluding hotels/hostels, residential institutions such as student halls of residence and care homes for children and elderly people. Dwellings also includes non-permanent structures used solely as a dwelling, such as houseboats and caravans.</p><p>(2) Fire and rescue services attended 2,385, 2,280 and 2,129 fires in industrial premises in England in 2013-14, 2014-15 and 2015-16 respectively. There were 6,132, 5,821 and 5,819 fires in commercial buildings in England in 2013-14, 2014-15 and 2015-16 respectively.</p><p>The latest figures were published in August in the Fire Statistics Monitor, which can be found here https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fire-statistics-monitor-april-2015-to-march-2016 while detailed tables can be found here https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables.</p><p>We have not estimated the economic and environmental costs of these fires.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-09-16T12:22:41.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576252/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576252/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576252/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-05","Fires","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many (1) domestic fires, and (2) fires in industrial and commercial buildings, were recorded in (a) 2013, (b) 2014, and (c) 2015; and what estimate they have made of the direct and indirect economic and environmental costs of those fires.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL1492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576253","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Locarno Group was formed in 2011. It consists of former senior Foreign and Commonwealth Office officials and functions as a high-level advisory group for the Foreign Secretary – offering strategic support and challenge on foreign policy issues.</p><p>The Locarno Group has met formally on eight occasions, most recently on 26 January 2015.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-12T11:16:50.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576253/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576253/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576253/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-05","Locarno Group","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when the Foreign and Commonwealth Office Locarno Group was last convened.","false","Biography information for Baroness Helic",,"Baroness Helic","HL1493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576254","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>We are aware of reports of alleged airstrikes on medical facilities in Yemen. It is important that the Saudi-led Coalition conducts thorough and conclusive investigations into incidents where it is alleged that International Humanitarian Law has been breached. They have the best insight into their own military procedures and will be able to conduct the most thorough and conclusive investigations. This is the standard we set ourselves and our allies. The Saudi led Coalition Joint Investigations Assessment Team announced the outcome of 8 investigations on 4 August.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-12T11:18:03.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576254/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576254/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576254/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-05","Yemen: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the Saudi-led coalition regarding attacks on medical facilities in Yemen, and what their policy is on that issue.","false","Biography information for Baroness Helic",,"Baroness Helic","HL1494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576255","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-19","<p>We have long advocated for action to tackle the problems of Rakhine for the benefit of all communities, and to end the mistreatment of the Muslim Rohingya minority. We therefore welcome the establishment of this Commission. The Parliamentary Under-Secretary for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Hon. Friend the Member for Reading West (Alok Sharma), issued a statement to this effect on 25 August. On 14 September he also held a telephone conversation with Mr Annan in which he conveyed the UK’s strong support for his appointment and mandate. We are clear that this is a Burmese conceived and led initiative, and that is as it should be. The UK is providing funding to support the work of the Kofi Annan Foundation.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-19T12:50:22.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576255/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576255/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576255/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-05","Rakhine State Advisory Commission","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what support they plan to give to the Commission on Rakhine State led by former UN Secretary General Kofi Annan.","false","Biography information for Baroness Helic",,"Baroness Helic","HL1495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576256","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-15","<p>The Government remains firmly committed to the initiative, now adopted by the EU, designed to inject momentum into Bosnia and Herzegovina's stalling reform process. We continue to work closely with EU, and other international partners, in order to help build a more stable, secure and prosperous BiH.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-15T15:16:33.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576256/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576256/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576256/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-05","Bosnia and Herzegovina: EU Enlargement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 24 November 2015 (HL3593), whether it is their policy to continue the UK–Germany Initiative on Bosnia and Herzegovina.","false","Biography information for Baroness Helic",,"Baroness Helic","HL1496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576257","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-15","<p>The Government remains concerned about the increasing tensions over the Republika Srpska referendum planned for 25 September. We, together with international partners, are calling on all parties to find a way forward that is line with Bosnia and Herzegovina’s constitution and the Constitutional Court’s rulings.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-15T15:18:02.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576257/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576257/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576257/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-05","Bosnia and Herzegovina: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact of the security and political stability of Bosnia and Herzegovina on the planned referendum in the entity of Republika Srpska on 25 September.","false","Biography information for Baroness Helic",,"Baroness Helic","HL1497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576258","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-19","<p>The UK Government, together with international partners, is pressing political leaders in Bosnia and Herzegovina to use domestic processes to find a constitutional solution to the issue of the referendum on 25 September. The UK is also engaging with EU partners on how to respond if the referendum does take place on 25th September.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-19T12:43:41.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576258/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576258/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576258/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-05","Bosnia and Herzegovina: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking ahead of the EU General Affairs Council on 20 September to engage their EU counterparts on the issue of imposing restrictive measures on individuals in Bosnia and Herzegovina who oppose those who will administer or facilitate the referendum on 25 September.","false","Biography information for Baroness Helic",,"Baroness Helic","HL1498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576259","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-19","<p>The Government is not aware of such delays. However, we remain vigilant and open to evidence of problems in this area, and have set up a mailbox where specific instances should be sent. The mailbox address is <a href="mailto:research@bis.gsi.gov.uk" target="_blank">research@bis.gsi.gov.uk</a>. If the noble Baroness was able to provide more information, we would be happy to look into it.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-09-19T13:37:26.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576259/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576259/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576259/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-05","EU Grants and Loans","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the remarks by the Minister for Universities and Science that it would be “business as usual” for EU funding committees until the UK leaves the EU, why there have been delays in communicating the outcomes of funding decisions since the referendum; and what steps they are taking to ensure that there are sufficient staff and resources available promptly to process and decide on applications for EU funding to ensure that those funds reach projects.","false","Biography information for Baroness Janke",,"Baroness Janke","HL1499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576260","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-16","<p>Departments will continue to have the resource available to sign all projects in the ordinary course of business prior to the Autumn Statement, as detailed by the Chief Secretary in his letter of 12<sup>th</sup> August 2016. A of copy this letter is available in the Library of the House.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2016-09-16T09:48:42.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576260/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576260/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576260/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-05","EU Grants and Loans","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the remarks by the Chancellor of the Exchequer that “structural and investment funds projects signed before the Autumn Statement and Horizon research funding granted before we leave the EU will be guaranteed by the Treasury after we leave”, what steps they are taking to ensure that there will be adequate staff resources in government departments to handle EU funding applications promptly in the months up to that Statement.","false","Biography information for Baroness Janke",,"Baroness Janke","HL1500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576261","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-19","<p>The Treasury does not hold information about individual EU funded projects, so the detailed information requested could only be provided at disproportionate cost. Information about EU funded projects in the UK is in the public domain, e.g. a list of European Structural and Investment Funds beneficiaries is available on Gov.uk.</p><p> </p><p>In line with the Chief Secretary’s letter of 12<sup>th</sup> August, a copy of which has been deposited in the Libraries of the House, further details will be provided ahead of the Autumn Statement.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2016-09-19T09:15:55.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576261/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576261/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576261/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-05","EU Grants and Loans","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the remarks by the Chancellor of the Exchequer that “structural and investment funds projects signed before the Autumn Statement and Horizon research funding granted before we leave the EU will be guaranteed by the Treasury after we leave”, whether they intend to publish the number and value of contracts signed for each funding stream approved between the Chancellor’s announcement and the Autumn Statement.","false","Biography information for Baroness Janke",,"Baroness Janke","HL1501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576262","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-09","<p>I would like to thank the Constitution Committee for their report ‘Intergovernmental relations in the UK’ which was published in March 2015. As the former Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster noted in his initial response to the Committee, the report was timely as it followed the launch of a joint review of intergovernmental relations in the United Kingdom which was commissioned by the Prime Minister and heads of the Devolved Administrations at the Joint Ministerial Committee Plenary JMC(P) meeting in December 2014.</p><p>The review was undertaken by senior officials within each of the four administrations and the recommendations have been considered. It is anticipated that the review’s findings will be considered at the next Plenary meeting of the JMC later this year. The Committee has agreed that the Government issue a full response to its report following the JMC(P) meeting.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-09-09T11:15:50.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576262/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576262/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576262/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-05","Devolution","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they intend to respond to the Constitution Committee’s report, <i>Inter-governmental relations in the United Kingdom</i>, published on 27 March 2015.","false","Biography information for Lord Lexden",,"Lord Lexden","HL1502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576263","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-19","<p>On 1 July 2016, the European Council unanimously agreed to prolong economic sanctions targeting specific sectors of the Russian economy until 31 January 2017. The EU remains united in its strategy of resolving the Ukraine crisis through diplomacy underpinned by robust sanctions pressure. All EU Member States have agreed that the duration of the sanctions is linked to the complete implementation of the Minsk agreements.</p><p>The UK has a strong relationship with the Republic of Cyprus. With respect to the Cyprus settlement talks, we commend the courageous leadership of President Anastasiasdes and Mr Akıncı. As The Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Rutland and Melton (Sir Alan Duncan) made clear during his visit to Cyprus on 6-8 September, the UK will continue to support the efforts of both communities to reunite Cyprus.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-19T12:43:01.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576263/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576263/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576263/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-05","Russia: Sanctions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 25 July (HL1110), whether they are at variance with the government of the Republic of Cyprus regarding its unilateral call for an end to current trade and economic sanctions imposed on Russia by the EU; and what assessment they have made of whether that call casts doubts on the Republic of Cyprus' sincerity and dependability in other areas of common interest, including the Talks Process.","false","Biography information for Lord Maginnis of Drumglass",,"Lord Maginnis of Drumglass","HL1503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576264","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>The 2015 Commercial Victimisation Survey found that 24 per cent of agriculture, forestry and fishing premises had experienced at least one incident of crime (excluding online crime) a statistically significant fall of six percentage points compared with the 2013 Survey. Vandalism, theft and burglary were the most common crime types experienced by this sector. On average there were 330 incidents of online crime per 1,000 premises in this sector, which is around a third of the incidence rate for ‘traditional’ crimes against this sector. The majority of online crime incidents involved computer viruses.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-09-12T14:54:10.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576264/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576264/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576264/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-05","Rural Areas: Crime","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact of rural crime on farmers and other rural businesses.","false","Biography information for Baroness McIntosh of Pickering",,"Baroness McIntosh of Pickering","HL1504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576265","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-15","<p>Officials from our Consulate-General in Jerusalem have discussed the remarks about litigation with Palestinian officials and politicians. We continue to urge a negotiated solution to the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, although we have not called for a return to direct bilateral negotiations without preconditions. The UK’s vision for a future two-state solution is clear. It should be based on 1967 borders with agreed land swaps, Jerusalem as the shared capital of both states, and with a just, fair and agreed settlement for refugees.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-15T15:24:43.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576265/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576265/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576265/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-05","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the remarks regarding litigation over the Balfour Declaration made by the Foreign Affairs Minister and the President of the Palestinian Authority, what representations they have made to the Palestinian Authority regarding a return to direct negotiations without preconditions between it and the government of Israel.","false","Biography information for Lord Palmer of Childs Hill",,"Lord Palmer of Childs Hill","HL1505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576266","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-15","<p>Officials from our Consulate-General in Jerusalem have discussed the remarks with Palestinian officials and politicians.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-15T15:26:49.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576266/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576266/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576266/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-05","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the remarks made by the Foreign Affairs Minister of the Palestinian Authority calling for legal action against the UK over the Balfour Declaration, what representations they have made to the Palestinian Authority regarding the delegitimising of the State of Israel.","false","Biography information for Lord Palmer of Childs Hill",,"Lord Palmer of Childs Hill","HL1506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576267","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-15","<p>We continue to believe that recognition of genocide should be a matter for competent courts, decided by judges after consideration of all the evidence available in the context of a credible judicial process. A recent example was in March 2016, when the Trial Chamber of the International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia (ICTY) convicted Radovan Karadžić of one count of genocide (along with other crimes) and sentenced him to forty years imprisonment. The UK is fully committed to the principle that there must be no impunity for the most serious international crimes.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-15T15:27:24.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576267/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576267/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576267/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-05","Genocide","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 19 July (HL1204), whether they will now list the competent courts that can recognise genocide.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL1507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576268","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-15","<p>Following the failed coup on 15 July the Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Rutland and Melton (Sir Alan Duncan), travelled to Ankara on 20 and 21 July to express the Government's support for Turkey's democratically elected government. He also emphasised to senior politicians the need for Turkey to adhere to international human rights obligations in the aftermath of the coup and during the imposition of a state of emergency, including press freedom and the rule of law. The Government continues to follow events there closely.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-15T15:19:10.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576268/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576268/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576268/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-05","Turkey: Press Freedom","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the effect on relations between the UK and Turkey of the closure of media outlets in Turkey following the attempted coup of 15 July.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL1508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576269","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-19","<p>The Government is aware of news reporting of Turkish brokerage houses’ research being sought by the Turkish authorities, but the impact on UK-Turkish financial services transactions is as yet unclear. It is not unusual for governments to refer to research undertaken by independent researchers and analysts. We have and continue to emphasise that the Turkish Government's response to the coup attempt must be demonstrably lawful and proportionate. We will continue to engage with the Turkish Government on its response to the coup attempt and monitor the situation closely.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-19T15:18:34.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576269/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576269/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576269/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-05","Turkey: Financial Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the effect on UK–Turkish financial services transactions of the reported collection by the Turkish government of client research carried out by Turkish brokerage houses following the attempted coup of 15 July.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL1509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576270","Department for International Trade","false","2016-09-19","<p>The attempted coup of 15 July came as a surprise to everyone including UK investors in Turkey. The democratically elected government remains in power. Its policies, relating to international investors, remain the same or have been improved, with the aim of encouraging more foreign direct investment. UK investors were quick to confirm their intention to maintain or enhance their investments. We have consulted widely with the UK investor community, their message is clear; they are in Turkey for the long term and do not believe the events of 15 July have altered the economic fundamentals or the business case for continuing to invest in the market.</p>",,"Lord Price",,"2016-09-19T15:46:33.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576270/answer","Biography information for Lord Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576270/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576270/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-09-05","Turkey: Overseas Investment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the implications for inward investment in Turkey by UK companies and financial institutions of the attempted coup of 15 July.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL1510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576271","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-16","<p>There is no legal prohibition on consuming alcohol on the premises of Richmond House, Wellington House and 22–26 Whitehall. However, the residing departments do not have alcohol licences and cannot, therefore, sell alcohol on the premises.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2016-09-16T09:48:08.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576271/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576271/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576271/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-05","Financial Services: Islam","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord O’Neill of Gatley on 7 April (HL7296), whether alcohol can be sold or consumed on the premises of Richmond House, Wellington House and 22–26 Whitehall.","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL1511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576272","Home Office","false","2016-09-16","<p>Having considered the very detailed responses received to the consultation exercise, we intend to make the statutory rules governing the regulation and management of immigration short term holding facilities in due course.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-09-16T12:23:45.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576272/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576272/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576272/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-05","Detention Centres","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they propose to publish the Short Term Holding Facility Rules and the statutory guidance governing such facilities following the most recent consultation on those rules, which ended on 14 April.","false","Biography information for Lord Ramsbotham",,"Lord Ramsbotham","HL1512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576273","Home Office","false","2016-09-16","<p>Our records currently indicate that since Royal Assent, 30 children who meet the criteria in the Immigration Act 2016 have been transferred to the UK. This is provisional management information that is subject to change. It has not been assured to the standard of Official Statistics.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-09-16T13:03:31.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576273/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576273/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576273/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-05","Refugees: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many unaccompanied child refugees have been accepted into the UK since the passing of the Immigration Act 2016.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL1513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576274","Home Office","false","2016-09-16","<p>We intend to resettle up to 20,000 Syrians in need of protection during this Parliament. We will continue to work closely with the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) to identify appropriate cases, prioritising the most vulnerable. The numbers resettled in a particular period will depend on a range of factors including the flow of referrals from UNHCR in the field and the availability of suitable accommodation and care packages in the UK. We continue to work closely with local authorities to manage the arrival of the Syrian refugees in to the resettlement places they have pledged. We will manage the flows based on need and in support of the wellbeing of the people and communities involved, rather than rushing to meet arbitrary targets. However, we are clear that we want to help as many people as we can as quickly as possible.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-09-16T13:14:36.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576274/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576274/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576274/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-05","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to ensure that their pledge to accept 20,000 Syrian refugees by 2020 is honoured.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL1514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576275","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-12","<p>In total, British ships have rescued over 24,000 migrants in the Mediterranean since April 2015.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-09-12T14:56:33.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576275/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576275/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576275/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-05","Refugees: Mediterranean Sea","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many migrants have been rescued by British ships because they have found themselves in difficulty crossing the Mediterranean or Adriatic seas.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL1515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576276","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-13","<p>From August 2014 to 31 March 2016, the net additional costs of counter-Daesh activity in Iraq and Syria were £265 million. These costs were met from a combination of the HM Treasury Special Reserve and the Deployed Military Activity Pool (DMAP). The £265 million is split into £45 million in financial year 2014-15, and £220 million in financial year 2015-16.</p><p>This activity was to support UK military activity to degrade and ultimately defeat Daesh. It has included airstrikes in support of coalition ground operations and airborne intelligence gathering operations in Iraq and Syria, as well as helping to train the Iraqi Security Forces and moderate Syrian opposition.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-09-13T15:54:14.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576276/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576276/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576276/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-05","Middle East: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what has been their total expenditure on military action in Syria and Iraq.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL1516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576277","Department for International Development","false","2016-09-16","<p>The Department for International Development is providing support to refugees in a number of countries in the Middle East including in Lebanon, Jordan, Turkey, Yemen and the Occupied Palestinian Territories. In financial year 2015/16 our support totalled more than £204 million.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-16T11:02:52.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576277/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576277/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576277/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-09-05","Middle East: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much funding is given annually by the UK to assist refugee projects in the Middle East.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL1517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576278","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-15","<p>Prison chaplains of all faiths make a valuable contribution to offender management, both in the provision of pastoral care and theological education, and as a safeguard against the spread of extremist ideologies. There are established pre-appointment checks in place for all prison chaplaincy positions, including Counter Terrorist Check (CTC) security clearance and the scrutiny of professional credentials.</p><p> </p><p>The Government response to the review into Islamist Extremism included a commitment to strengthen the due diligence process for the recruitment of prison chaplains. This policy is still being developed, and will supplement rather than replace existing arrangements. The checks can be applied to all prospective prison chaplains, of any faith, before a final offer of employment is made.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-09-15T11:24:54.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576278/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576278/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576278/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-05","Prisons: Ministers of Religion","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the publication of the review of Islamist extremism in prisons and the probation and youth justice services, in what ways they plan to change the vetting of prison chaplains and build on existing good practice, including vetting to counter-terrorism level.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Rochester",,"The Lord Bishop of Rochester","HL1518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576279","Department of Health","false","2016-09-13","<p>A draft version of NHS England’s Research and Development Plan for 2016/17 is currently out with stakeholders for information and comment. A copy of the final version will therefore be published on NHS England’s website in due course once it has been agreed and approved.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-09-13T16:39:14.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576279/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576279/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576279/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-05","NHS: Research","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to publish the NHS England Research and Development plan for 2016–17; if so, when, and if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Sharkey",,"Lord Sharkey","HL1519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576280","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-09","<p>The Government has a clear position, which has remained consistent for around 70 years: UK State Pensions are payable worldwide and uprated abroad where we have a legal requirement to do so - for example in countries where a reciprocal agreement is in place that allows for uprating. There are no plans to change this or to assess the impact of British citizens’ choosing to retire abroad.</p>",,"Lord Freud","HL1521 ; HL1522","2016-09-09T12:03:42.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576280/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576280/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576280/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-05","State Retirement Pensions: British Nationals Abroad","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to review their policy of freezing state pensions of British citizens residing in overseas countries, where there is no existing reciprocal social security arrangement in place.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of St Albans",,"The Lord Bishop of St Albans","HL1520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576281","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-09","<p>The Government has a clear position, which has remained consistent for around 70 years: UK State Pensions are payable worldwide and uprated abroad where we have a legal requirement to do so - for example in countries where a reciprocal agreement is in place that allows for uprating. There are no plans to change this or to assess the impact of British citizens’ choosing to retire abroad.</p>",,"Lord Freud","HL1520 ; HL1522","2016-09-09T12:03:42.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576281/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576281/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576281/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-05","State Retirement Pensions: British Nationals Abroad","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to negotiate extending reciprocal social security arrangements to overseas countries so as to facilitate an annual increase in the state pension for British citizens who retire to those countries.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of St Albans",,"The Lord Bishop of St Albans","HL1521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576282","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-09","<p>The Government has a clear position, which has remained consistent for around 70 years: UK State Pensions are payable worldwide and uprated abroad where we have a legal requirement to do so - for example in countries where a reciprocal agreement is in place that allows for uprating. There are no plans to change this or to assess the impact of British citizens’ choosing to retire abroad.</p>",,"Lord Freud","HL1520 ; HL1521","2016-09-09T12:03:42.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576282/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576282/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576282/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-05","State Retirement Pensions: British Nationals Abroad","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the average annual cost or saving to the public purse when a British citizen chooses to retire abroad rather than remain in the UK, assuming a continuing increase in the state pension.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of St Albans",,"The Lord Bishop of St Albans","HL1522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576283","Home Office","false","2016-09-16","<p>The register of licensed Tier 4 sponsors is published daily and will continue to be. Sponsors that lose their licence as a result of non-compliance are removed from the published list of sponsors.</p><p>No information is routinely published regarding sponsors found not to be compliant. In January 2015 data was published showing Tier 4 sponsors whose status appeared as revoked from 2010 to 2014. This information is available at: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/tier-4-sponsors-whose-status-appeared-as-revoked-from-2010-to-2014</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-09-16T13:03:10.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576283/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576283/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576283/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-05","Visas: Overseas Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to ensure that regular updates of the list of Tier 4 visa sponsors are published when sponsors are found not to be compliant with government requirements.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL1523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576284","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-19","<p>We consider that any attempt to change the meaning of the acronym GMT is likely to result in confusion.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-09-19T13:36:17.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576284/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576284/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576284/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-05","Greenwich Mean Time","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to change the meaning of the acronym GMT from Greenwich Mean Time to Greenwich Meridian Time.","false","Biography information for Lord Tanlaw",,"Lord Tanlaw","HL1524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576285","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-26","<p>As the reference frame for the Global Positioning System (GPS) is established through a mathematical interpretation of satellite radio signals, rather than a physical meridian, it is not conceptually appropriate to represent it in the same way as other meridians have historically been marked at Greenwich.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-09-26T13:14:04.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576285/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576285/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576285/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-05","Global Positioning System","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to identify accurately the GPS Prime Meridian with a corresponding marker at the correct location in Greenwich Park.","false","Biography information for Lord Tanlaw",,"Lord Tanlaw","HL1525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576286","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Government has no plans to review the use of British Summer Time.</p><p> </p><p>In 2012, the Government published a review of the available evidence concerning the likely effects of moving to Central European Time (also known as Daylight Saving time) in the UK. This is attached, but is also available on the Government website at the following link.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/34587/12-1036-review-evidence-putting-clocks-forward.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/34587/12-1036-review-evidence-putting-clocks-forward.pdf</a></p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-09-12T14:49:12.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576286/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576286/answer","Attachment to HL1526 - review-evidence-putting-clocks-forward.pdf","Attachment to HL1526 - review-evidence-putting-clocks-forward.pdf","Review on Daylight Saving time","Review on Daylight Saving time","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576286/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-05","Summertime","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to review the use of British Summer Time, and what assessment they have made of the possible impact of maintaining BST throughout the year.","false","Biography information for Lord Tanlaw",,"Lord Tanlaw","HL1526"
