rong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total number of sentences referred to the Court of Appeal</p></td><td><p>117</p></td><td><p>82</p></td><td><p>70</p></td><td><p>122</p></td><td><p>136</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total number of sentences that were increased</p></td><td><p>95</p></td><td><p>62</p></td><td><p>61</p></td><td><p>106</p></td><td><p>102</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total number of sentences that remained unchanged</p></td><td><p>22</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>16</p></td><td><p>34</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The number of referrals under the unduly lenient sentence scheme that have been rejected due to falling outside the remit of the scheme in each of the last five years is set out below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of referrals that have been rejected due to the offence falling outside the remit of the scheme</p></td><td><p>62</p></td><td><p>75</p></td><td><p>131</p></td><td><p>194</p></td><td><p>228</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of referrals received out of time</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>12</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>16</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright","44884 ; 44885 ; 44886 ; 44887 ; 44888","2016-09-12T15:54:05.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576357/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576357/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576357/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-09-05","Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many applications under the unduly lenient sentence scheme have been rejected due to falling outside the remit of that scheme in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","44889"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576358","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-08","<p>Workforce planning is primarily the responsibility of each department to determine based on their individual operational and policy requirements. Each department has their own spending agreements with HM Treasury for this Parliament and are responsible for ensuring they have the right workforce and capability in place to deliver their commitments.</p><p>Earlier this year, departments published their Single Departmental Plans, setting out the key programmes of work required to deliver the Government’s Manifesto commitments. Departments have been developing plans to ensure they have the workforce capacity and capability required to deliver their Single Departmental Plans.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-09-08T08:48:37.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576358/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576358/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576358/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-05","Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what plans he has to change the staff headcount across the Civil Service in each of the next four years; and what the projected expenditure on staff is in that time period.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","44983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576359","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-08","<p>Like other Civil Servants, and the wider workforce, Prison Officers can now choose to retire at their State Pension Age (SPA) should they wish to do so, unless they have a protected lower pension age allowing them to retire at age 55, 60 or 65.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-09-08T16:57:32.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576359/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576359/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576359/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-05","Prison Officers : Retirement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will bring forward proposals to bring prison officers' retirement age into line with that of staff in the police force, fire service and armed forces.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","44981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576360","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-09","<p>The Cabinet Office does not collect data on behalf of Government on the receipt of credit card fees from people paying for services offered by its departments and agencies. If available, individual departments and agencies will hold this information.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-09-09T12:45:39.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576360/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576360/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576360/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-05","Government Departments: Credit Cards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, from which sources does the Government receive credit card fees from people paying for services offered by its departments and agencies; and what the total amount received was in (a) 2013-14, (b) 2014-15 and (c) 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","45025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576361","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-08","<p>The funds mentioned are covered under the Chancellor’s recent announcement on EU funding, available at this link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/chancellor-philip-hammond-guarantees-eu-funding-beyond-date-uk-leaves-the-eu" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/chancellor-philip-hammond-guarantees-eu-funding-beyond-date-uk-leaves-the-eu</a></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-09-08T10:39:06.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576361/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576361/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576361/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-05","Countryside Stewardship Scheme and LEADER Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will continue to make funding available for new and existing LEADER and Countryside Stewardship schemes when the UK ceases to be a participant of the Common Agricultural Policy on leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","45072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576362","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Open Banking Working Group was created at the request of the government to explore options for allowing customers to use their bank data in a safe, secure and efficient manner. The Group published its report in February 2016. The conclusions reached represent the views of the Working Group and are not government policy.</p><p> </p><p>Subsequently, the Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) issued the final report of its investigation into retail banking on 9 August 2016. As part of this, the CMA requires nine leading UK banks to create an open API (Application Programming Interface) to allow access to customer account information as set out in the revised Payment Services Directive (PSDII), which will come into force in January 2018. Informed consent, data protection and cyber security are key considerations in the PSDII, and the government will be consulting on the transposition of this directive shortly.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","45074","2016-09-08T10:37:48.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576362/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576362/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576362/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-05","Bank Services: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 4.3.2 of the Open Banking Standard report published in February 2016, what assessment the Government has made of the (a) cyber security, (b) data protection and (c) fraud risks an open banking environment introduces.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","45073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576363","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Open Banking Working Group was created at the request of the government to explore options for allowing customers to use their bank data in a safe, secure and efficient manner. The Group published its report in February 2016. The conclusions reached represent the views of the Working Group and are not government policy.</p><p> </p><p>Subsequently, the Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) issued the final report of its investigation into retail banking on 9 August 2016. As part of this, the CMA requires nine leading UK banks to create an open API (Application Programming Interface) to allow access to customer account information as set out in the revised Payment Services Directive (PSDII), which will come into force in January 2018. Informed consent, data protection and cyber security are key considerations in the PSDII, and the government will be consulting on the transposition of this directive shortly.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","45073","2016-09-08T10:37:48.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576363/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576363/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576363/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-05","Bank Services: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Open Banking Standard report published in February 2016, how the Government plans to ensure that customers provide informed consent when using open banking services.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","45074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576364","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-08","<p>The funds mentioned are covered under the Chancellor’s recent announcement on EU funding, available at this link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/chancellor-philip-hammond-guarantees-eu-funding-beyond-date-uk-leaves-the-eu" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/chancellor-philip-hammond-guarantees-eu-funding-beyond-date-uk-leaves-the-eu</a></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-09-08T10:43:08.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576364/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576364/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576364/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-05","Countryside Stewardship Scheme and LEADER Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans his Department has to ensure that the LEADER and Countryside Stewardship schemes continue to be funded when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","44984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576365","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Married Couple’s Allowance (MCA) is an additional allowance for married couples worth between £322 and £835.50 per couple in 2016-17. Prior to 2000-01, MCA was available to all married couples irrespective of age, but on the introduction of the tax credit system it remained available to married couples where at least one of them was born before 6 April 1935.</p><p>The estimated cost and the estimated number of claimants of MCA for the financial years 2002-03 to 2015-16 are given in the table below.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong>Married Couple's Allowance</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Cost (£millions)</p></td><td><p>Number of Claimants (000s)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2002-03</p></td><td><p>450</p></td><td><p>1160</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2003-04</p></td><td><p>610</p></td><td><p>1510</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2004-05</p></td><td><p>590</p></td><td><p>1450</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005-06</p></td><td><p>530</p></td><td><p>1320</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006-07</p></td><td><p>520</p></td><td><p>1230</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007-08</p></td><td><p>450</p></td><td><p>1050</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>*</p></td><td><p>*</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>440</p></td><td><p>890</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>340</p></td><td><p>670</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>400</p></td><td><p>760</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>360</p></td><td><p>650</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>320</p></td><td><p>570</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>285</p></td><td><p>490</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>245</p></td><td><p>420</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>*Data not currently available</p><p> </p><p>Up to 2012-13 these estimates are based on the Survey of Personal Incomes (SPI) for the years concerned. Later years are projected from the 2012-13 SPI using the Office for Budget Responsibility’s Autumn Statement 2015 economic and fiscal outlook. Data for 2000-01, 2001-02 and 2008-09 are not currently available.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","44905","2016-09-08T16:00:30.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576365/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576365/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576365/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-05","Married Couple's Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the cost to the public purse was of providing the married couples allowance in each financial year since 2001.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","44906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576366","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Married Couple’s Allowance (MCA) is an additional allowance for married couples worth between £322 and £835.50 per couple in 2016-17. Prior to 2000-01, MCA was available to all married couples irrespective of age, but on the introduction of the tax credit system it remained available to married couples where at least one of them was born before 6 April 1935.</p><p>The estimated cost and the estimated number of claimants of MCA for the financial years 2002-03 to 2015-16 are given in the table below.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong>Married Couple's Allowance</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Cost (£millions)</p></td><td><p>Number of Claimants (000s)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2002-03</p></td><td><p>450</p></td><td><p>1160</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2003-04</p></td><td><p>610</p></td><td><p>1510</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2004-05</p></td><td><p>590</p></td><td><p>1450</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005-06</p></td><td><p>530</p></td><td><p>1320</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006-07</p></td><td><p>520</p></td><td><p>1230</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007-08</p></td><td><p>450</p></td><td><p>1050</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>*</p></td><td><p>*</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>440</p></td><td><p>890</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>340</p></td><td><p>670</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>400</p></td><td><p>760</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>360</p></td><td><p>650</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>320</p></td><td><p>570</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>285</p></td><td><p>490</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>245</p></td><td><p>420</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>*Data not currently available</p><p> </p><p>Up to 2012-13 these estimates are based on the Survey of Personal Incomes (SPI) for the years concerned. Later years are projected from the 2012-13 SPI using the Office for Budget Responsibility’s Autumn Statement 2015 economic and fiscal outlook. Data for 2000-01, 2001-02 and 2008-09 are not currently available.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","44906","2016-09-08T16:00:30.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576366/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576366/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576366/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-05","Married Couple's Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many couples claimed the married couples allowance in each financial year since 2001.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","44905"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576367","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-12","<p>Income tax and national insurance contributions are charged on total income after allowances and reliefs therefore it is not possible to determine how much income tax or national insurance contributions were generated solely from self-employment income sources from the courier sector.</p><p> </p><p>Tax credit expenditure received by this sector could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-09-12T10:51:41.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576367/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576367/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576367/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-05","Courier Services: Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much tax and national insurance revenue was received from the self-employed courier sector in each of the last three years; and how much tax credit expenditure that sector received in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","44938"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576368","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-13","<p>The Neighbourhood Planning Bill will strengthen neighbourhood planning, by requiring local planning authorities and others who decide planning applications to have regard to neighbourhood plans that have been independently examined, once the decision has been taken to put the plan to a referendum.The Bill would also ensure plans have full legal weight at an earlier stage of the process, as soon as the outcome of the referendum is announced, and make it easier to ensure plans can be kept up to date.</p><p>These measures are in addition to existing safeguards that ensure neighbourhood plans are given proper consideration, including existing powers for communities to request that the Secretary of State ‘calls-in’ planning applications for his own determination, and new requirements introduced in the Housing and Planning Act, that will require any conflict with a made neighbourhood plan to be set out in the committee report that will inform a planning committee decision.</p><p>Furthermore, national planning policy is clear that where a planning application conflicts with a neighbourhood plan that has been brought into force, planning permission should not normally be granted, and that decision-makers may give weight to policies in emerging neighbourhood plans according to the stage of preparation of the plan, the extent of unresolved objections, and the degree of consistency with the National Planning Policy Framework.</p><p>In the light of these safeguards, the government does not support a right of appeal for those opposed to a decision to grant planning permission, which would delay the building of the new homes we need.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2016-09-13T16:39:25.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576368/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576368/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576368/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-05","Neighbourhood Development Plans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to enable communities with neighbourhood plans that are (a) complete and (b) being developed to appeal against planning decisions that conflict with that plan.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","44881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576369","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-12","<p>We do not provide funding specifically for children and adults in social care. Local authorities were provided with formula grant in the period 2010-11 to 2012-13, and Revenue Support Grant from 2013-14 onwards, both of which are unringfenced and it is a matter for local discretion how this is spent.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","45021","2016-09-12T15:49:14.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576369/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576369/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576369/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576369/answer/previousversion/10013","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-05","Social Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much funding his Department has given to support children and young adults in social care in (a) St Helens North, (b) Merseyside and (c) the UK in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","45022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576370","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Government welcomes local community initiatives that tackle hate crime and intolerance. In July, we published the cross-Government Hate Crime Action Plan in which we committed Government to tackling all forms of hate crime including race hate crime. We are currently supporting True Vision, an on-line hate crime reporting site, as well as the Anne Frank Trust and Streetwise, who work in schools to tackle prejudice and intolerance. In addition, the Hate Crime Action Plan referred to 'community-led solutions' - a new initiative funded by the Home Office to explore innovative ways in which communities in the North East would be eligible to apply once the scheme is launched.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-09-08T14:42:45.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576370/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576370/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576370/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-05","Community Relations: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to support the work of anti-racism groups in North East England and celebrate the support shown for migrants and refugees in Newcastle following the vote to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","45075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576371","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Government is committed to maintaining the right of local electorates to approve or veto excessive council tax rises in a local referendum. Decisions on the threshold are made annually as part of the Local Government Finance Settlement.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-09-08T14:38:36.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576371/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576371/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576371/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-05","Council Tax: Increases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the Government's policy is on the maximum threshold for council tax increases in England in (a) 2019-20, (b) 2020-21 and (c) 2021-22.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","45063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576372","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-08","<p>Government does not estimate local authority net revenue expenditure. Local authorities estimate how they intend to spend their money for the next financial year and submit this information in Revenue Account (RA) budget returns. The returns from all 443 local authorities in England are compiled by the Department for Communities and Local Government. Revenue Outturn statistics published by DCLG at the end of the financial year show how local authorities actually allocate their expenditure. The latest information on the amount of net revenue expenditure estimated by local authorities in England is for 2016/17. It is available here: https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/532932/RA_Budget_2016-17_Statistical_Release.pdf</p><p>Local authority core spending power provides an estimate of the amount of funding available to local authorities. Local authority core spending power figures setting out indicative figures for the potential income from core components for 2016/17-2019/20 are available here: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/core-spending-power-final-local-government-finance-settlement-2016-to-2017</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-09-08T14:41:47.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576372/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576372/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576372/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-05","Local Government Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate the Government has made of the (a) amount and (b) proportion that net revenue expenditure by local authorities will increase in England in (i) 2017-18, (ii) 2018-19 and (iii) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","45034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576373","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-12","<p>We do not provide funding specifically for children and adults in social care. Local authorities were provided with formula grant in the period 2010-11 to 2012-13, and Revenue Support Grant from 2013-14 onwards, both of which are unringfenced and it is a matter for local discretion how this is spent.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","45022","2016-09-12T15:49:14.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576373/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576373/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576373/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576373/answer/previousversion/10011","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-05","Social Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much funding per head his Department has given to support children and young adults in social care in (a) St Helens North, (b) Merseyside and (c) the UK in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","45021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576374","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Department does not estimate future yields from business rates for specific local authorities. National level estimates of yield from business rates are available from the Office for Budget Responsibility.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-09-08T10:15:23.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576374/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576374/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576374/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-05","Non-domestic Rates: Dorset","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate the Government has made of the  potential annual proportion increase in yield from business rates available for local authorities in Dorset, Poole and Bournemouth in (a) 2019-20, (b) 2020-21 and (c) 2021-22.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","45035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576375","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government does not publish guidance on local authority consultations. However, Local authorities should have regard to the rules on data protection when dealing with any personal information about residents, including personal information contained on consultation responses.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-09-08T14:39:58.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576375/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576375/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576375/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-05","Local Government: Public Consultation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what guidance his Department has issued on whether responses from residents to public consultation questionnaires issued by local authorities should be anonymous or identified by name and address.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","45036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576376","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-08","<p>Over the last three years, one local authority held a referendum to increase council tax beyond the threshold. A referendum was held on Bedfordshire Police and Crime Commissioner’s proposal to increase council tax.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-09-08T14:40:22.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576376/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576376/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576376/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-05","Council Tax: Increases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which local authorities in England have held referendums seeking increases in council tax beyond the maximum threshold in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","45037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576377","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-13","<p>The 2012 reinvigorated Right to Buy scheme increased maximum discounts and, for the first time ever, introduced a requirement to replace every additional sale (i.e. one that has come about as a result of the increased discounts) nationally with another property through acquisition or new supply. There is a rolling 3 years deadline for local authorities to use the receipts from additional Right to Buy sales for new affordable housing – and councils are delivering, replacing more than one for one within the deadline. <br> <br> Right to Buy sales by local authority (Table 691) and local authority starts and acquisitions (Table 693) can be accessed at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-social-housingsales" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-social-housingsales <br> </a><br> Figures are not available at a constituency level.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2016-09-13T16:37:00.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576377/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576377/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576377/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-05","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many social houses were (a) built and (b) sold under the Right to Buy scheme in (i) Ellesmere Port and Neston constituency, (ii) Cheshire West and Chester and (iii) England in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","45027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576378","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-08","<p>I refer my honourable friend to my answer to question 44837, answered on 7th September.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-09-08T06:50:03.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576378/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576378/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576378/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-05","Sportsgrounds: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the adequacy of wheelchair access at sports venues.","false","Biography information for Mrs Flick Drummond","Portsmouth South","Mrs Flick Drummond","45033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576379","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-08","<p>The childhood obesity plan was developed and drafted by Department of Health with input from departments across Government, including the Department for Culture, Media and Sport. DCMS will continue to work with DH on the implementation of the actions within the plan.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-09-08T11:10:16.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576379/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576379/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576379/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-05","Children: Obesity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what the role of her Department was in drafting the Government's childhood obesity plan.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","44972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576380","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-08","<p>Effective working relationships between network operators and landowners, including avoiding costly and time-consuming litigation, will remain in the interests of both parties. The reforms will not be retrospective and the new valuation basis will have no impact on existing agreements.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s impact assessment on the reformed Code can be found here:</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/407579/Annex_4_Electronic_Communications_Code_Reform_IA_-_DCMS075.pdf.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-09-08T15:53:10.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576380/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576380/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576380/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-05","Mobile Phones: Aerials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of moving from the current system of rooftop valuation for mobile network base stations to a no scheme valuation model on (a) the supply of sites, (b) the revenues received by Newcastle City Council and other public sector organisations from rooftop rentals and (c) mobile phone operator profits.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","44955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576381","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-08","<p>Government remains committed to a Code that is fit for a digital economy, delivers improved coverage and connectivity for the UK, and greater investment in UK infrastructure . The revised Electronic Communications Code has been developed in discussion with colleagues across Government including the Department of Communities and Local Government.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-09-08T15:54:03.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576381/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576381/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576381/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-05","Mobile Phones: Aerials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions she has had with the Department for Communities and Local Government on how to replace the funding potentially lost to public sector organisations for rooftop rental as a result of the changes to rooftop valuation proposed in the Digital Economy Bill.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","44956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576382","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-12","<p>Following the Queen's Speech, the Digital Economy Bill has been introduced which includes measures to enable the Government to implement and review a new broadband Universal Service Obligation. We have asked Ofcom to undertake a detailed technical analysis on a range of factors that will impact on the design of the USO. Once we have considered Ofcom's report, we will consult on the detailed specifications for the USO which will be set in secondary legislation once the Bill has received Royal Assent.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-09-12T11:49:59.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576382/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576382/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576382/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-05","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the Queen's Speech 2016, if her Department will publish detailed plans to create the right for every household to access high speed broadband.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","44980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576383","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-12","<p>The London 2012 Olympic Games were a huge success with sold-out venues and the best British performance for over 100 years in winning 65 medals. The Games left a legacy of increased participation and world-class sporting venues which are now being used by our elite athletes as well as local communities.</p><p>The commitment from the Government immediately following the London 2012 Olympic Games to confirm and sustain Exchequer support for the UK Sport World Class Programme was a significant moment in underpinning the success of Rio, providing UK Sport, and the National Governing Bodies of sport, with the necessary financial support to invest in medal success across the Olympic and Paralympic sports.</p><p> </p><p>I am confident that this success will continue at the Rio 2016 Paralympics, and through to Tokyo in 2020 and beyond. Since 2012, UK Sport funded athletes have given back over 18,000 days visiting schools and local projects as part of our commitment to inspire the next generation.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-09-12T16:17:51.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576383/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576383/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576383/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-05","Olympic Games","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the effect of the success of the London 2012 Olympic Games on the success of the competitors at the Rio 2016 Olympic Games.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","44915"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576384","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-13","<p>During our public consultation we have listened to views across a range of issues in relation to the BBC, including Gaelic language broadcasting.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-09-13T11:40:29.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576384/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576384/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576384/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-05","Broadcasting: Celtic Languages","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions she has had on the BBC's investment in Gaelic broadcasting as part of the BBC Charter Review; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","44918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576385","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-08","<p>The number of serving personnel that will return from Germany as part of the planned rebasing in each year to 2020 is shown below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of service personnel</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>1,270</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>120</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2019</p></td><td><p>4,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2020</p></td><td><p>20 (drawdown)</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-09-08T13:57:11.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576385/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576385/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576385/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-05","Armed Forces: Germany","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many serving personnel will return from Germany as part of the planned rebasing in each year to 2020.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","44890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576386","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-09","<p>The Ministry of Defence has put in place a strategy to provide an alternative solution should CarillionAmey fail to sustain performance. The Department continues to assess CarillionAmey's performance to determine whether the implementation of this strategy is necessary.</p><p>I will be meeting senior CarillionAmey staff in September to hold them to account for their performance.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-09-09T12:56:12.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576386/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576386/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576386/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-05","Armed Forces: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate his Department has made of the potential cost of terminating and re-tendering the Carillion Amey housing contract.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","44893"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576387","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-08","<p>Following the recent instability in South Sudan, we reviewed our deployment and judged that we should proceed as planned. We are now assessing with UN leads and the Government of South Sudan the timelines for the deployment of our forces. We have already deployed a small team to support the UN Mission in South Sudan and to pave the way for further UK military personnel.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-09-08T14:38:58.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576387/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576387/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576387/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-05","South Sudan: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the effect of the recent violence and instability in South Sudan on the deployment plan of British armed forces as part of the UN peacekeeping mission in that country.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","44909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576388","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Ministry of Defence does not hold the information in the format requested.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-09-12T14:48:53.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576388/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576388/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576388/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-05","Married Quarters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many married quarter void properties are situated on each military base in the UK.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","44891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576389","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Department continually assesses the condition and thus the habitability of its housing stock, including void properties.</p><p>With the introduction of the Combined Accommodation Assessment System (CAAS) on 1 April 2016, all Service Family Accommodation (SFA) in the UK were subject to a physical survey and/or extrapolation from like properties on the same estate. Void properties were assessed as part of the survey programme.</p><p>For void properties, 92% were assessed as being at Decent Homes Standard (DHS) and 8% below. In line with the commitment given in the Armed Forces Covenant, SFA below DHS will not be allocated to incoming Service families. For families living in properties below the DHS they will be offered to move to a different property where we can.</p><p>Overall 83% SFA exceed the Decent Homes Standard.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-09-12T14:45:33.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576389/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576389/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576389/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-05","Married Quarters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 8 June 2016 to Question 38976, on married quarters, what assessment his Department has made of the habitability of the 10,187 void properties.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","44892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576390","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-08","<p>In the interest of National Security we cannot comment on specific details of cyber security attacks. However, cyber security is one of the Government’s top national security priorities and BEIS is continuing to work with government departments and the National Cyber Security Centre, as well as with industry partners, to ensure that the risks to the energy sector are understood and that appropriate mitigations are established.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-09-08T13:49:35.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576390/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576390/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576390/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-05","Energy: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many cyber-attacks there have been on the UK's national energy infrastructure in the past five years.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","44904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576391","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-13","<p>Between 1 September 2014 and 31 August 2016 there were 941 UK airstrikes in Iraq. Between 1 December 2015 and 31 August 2016 there were 63 UK airstrikes in Syria.</p><p>These strike numbers are constantly reviewed and updated by the Coalition to ensure records are as complete and accurate as possible. As such, past and future statements regarding statistics may differ to those given here.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-09-13T14:55:19.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576391/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576391/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/576391/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-05","Middle East: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many British airstrikes have been conducted in (a) Iraq from September 2014 to September 2016 and (b) Syria from December 2015 to September 2016.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","45023"
